    <button x="1125" y="55" height="40" disableUntilTicks="false" forever="false" kind="Observer" width="65" display="baseline">scenario-baseline</button>
    <monitor x="160" precision="17" y="45" height="60" fontSize="11" width="145" display="Symbolic stewards %">ifelse-value any? turtles [precision ((count turtles with [mobilization-status = "symbolic-steward"] / count turtles) * 100) 2] [0]</monitor>
  </widgets>
  <info>## Religious Environmental Mobilization Model

## WHAT IS IT?

This model is a theoretical agent-based simulation of religious environmental mobilization. It examines under what conditions religious environmental belief remains symbolic and under what conditions it becomes collective climate action. The model is designed for mechanism clarification rather than empirical prediction.

## HOW IT WORKS

The model represents 1,000 agents distributed across 20 religious communities. Agents vary in stewardship belief, trust in science, trust in religious leaders, political identity, climate risk exposure, perceived cost of activism, environmental concern, moral obligation, community norm strength, and mobilization score.

At each tick, agents update their climate risk exposure, environmental concern, moral obligation, community norm strength, and mobilization score. They are then classified into one of six statuses: passive, concerned, symbolic steward, norm supporter, mobilized, or resistant.

Religious communities differ by leader type. Leaders may be silent, moderate, activist, or skeptical. Activist leaders strengthen religious climate framing, while skeptical leaders weaken it.

## HOW TO USE IT

Use the scenario shortcut buttons on the right side of the interface to select a scenario. Then press setup and either press go or run 150.

The model includes the following scenarios:

baseline
high stewardship
high risk
activist leader
skeptical leader
high polarization
high capacity
risk + activist
risk + capacity
activist + capacity
combined activation
full alignment

The monitors on the left report the number and percentage of agents in different statuses, as well as average concern, moral obligation, community norm strength, mobilization score, and climate risk.

## THINGS TO NOTICE

Stewardship belief alone tends to increase symbolic stewardship rather than large-scale mobilization. Climate risk increases environmental concern but does not necessarily produce collective action. The strongest mobilization occurs when activist religious leadership is combined with institutional capacity and strong community norm formation. Skeptical leadership and political polarization can block mobilization.

## THINGS TO TRY

Try comparing the baseline, high stewardship, high risk, activist + capacity, and full alignment scenarios. Notice how mobilization changes when moral framing, institutional capacity, and participation thresholds interact.

## MODEL SCOPE

This is an abstract theoretical model. It does not represent a specific religious tradition, country, organization, or climate movement. The parameters are stylized and are intended to explore mechanisms rather than estimate real-world levels of religious climate activism.

</info>
